    "timestamp": "2024-06-27T15:03:00",
    "place": null,
    "description": "14 trip \n\nduring the winter laura and i began talking about a family road trip. it had been six years since we made it all the way to santa monica -- sid and annie were 8 and 5 then. not nearly as ambitious this time, just 2 weeks instead of 5, and certainly less miles. this meant \"the rings.\"\n\nthe rings are in south dakota, at a place called evan's plunge. i discovered them on my first cross country road trip, half a lifetime ago. it's a series of olympic-style rings suspended over an olympic-style pool, built up around a hot spring, or at least a lukewarm spring, with water in the 80s filtering through the pebble floor. \n\nwatching the other kids i realized the goal was to swing over the pool -- ring to ring, platform to platform -- without falling in, american ninja warrior style. i couldn't do it. i made an immediate vow to return but that was 24 years ago.\n\naround march laura forwarded me an article that a psychologist had written about the concept of a 14 trip. the idea is that, when a kid reaches 14, the off parent, due to job, schedule, whatever, should go on a trip with them 1 on 1. apparently 14 is a good age to show them that a world beyond the middle school hallways exists, among other benefits. sid would turn 14 this summer. \n\nnot much time passed before we decided it would be just sid and i. the article said it was important to favor authentic experiences, avoiding disney worlds, and to let the kid help plan. \"i want to see mountains\" was sid's initial reaction. jim and sherry had said glacier national park was awesome, so we made that our turnaround point. \n\nglacier is in montana, which turns out is dinosaur country. \"every age is dinosaur age\" sid recently assured when i questioned whether she'd outgrown them. we made reservations for a few dino adventures.\n\nwe planned departure around a jon batiste concert in western mass that never materialized for us. our return would be sid's birthday. the initial plan was to do the rings on the way out, by way of fireworks over mount rushmore on the fourth of july, except there aren't any, so we went counterclockwise instead, across the north first, looking to find fireworks in any small eastern montana town.",
    "data": null,
